  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT202-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">vāyilākap pukka tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ vāyiṉ maṟuttatu. </p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">refusing the door/mediation to the confidante who enters
          as a mediator. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT202">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l>nōmeṉ ṉeñcē nōmeṉ ṉeñcē</l>
          <l>puṉpulat tamaṉṟa ciṟiyilai neruñcik</l>
          <l>kaṭkiṉ putumalar muṭpayan tāaṅ</l>
          <l>kiṉiya ceytanaṅ kātala</l>
          <l>riṉṉā ceyta ṉōmeṉ ṉeñcē.</l>

        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Aches my heart. Aches my heart.</l>
          <l rend="indent">Since, just like the new flowers, sweet to the eye, bear thorns</l>
          <l rend="indent2">on the small-leaved Neruñci, <note place="foot">The choice of the plant Neruñci (whatever it is) might not be chance. There seems to be a connection between Neruñci and physical love; cf. KT 315 where HER shoulders are likened to it, while HE is compared with the sun.</note> grown dense in the grassy fields,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">our lover who did sweet things [to us],</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[now] does unsweet ones,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">aches my heart.</l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
